rticleHero_rubric__e4rjD ArticleHero_twoColRubric__8kY4w"><div class="ArticleRubric_root__HNhbf" id="rubric" data-flatplan-rubric="true"><a class="ArticleRubric_link__nl9hy" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/" data-action="click link - section rubric" data-label="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/" data-event-element="rubric">Culture</a></div></div><div class="ArticleHero_title__PQ4pC"><h1 class="ArticleTitle_root__VrZaG ArticleTitle_featureOrTwoCol__TRUC3 ArticleTitle_twoCol__8npP_" data-flatplan-title="true">How Daniel Radcliffe Outran Harry Potter</h1></div><div class="ArticleHero_dek__EqdkK" data-flatplan-description="true"><p class="ArticleDek_root__P3leE ArticleDek_twoCol__BtQqH">He was the world’s most famous child star. Then he had to figure out what came next.</p></div><div class="ArticleHero_byline__iFT6A ArticleHero_twoColByline__VhWQ_"><div class="ArticleBylines_root__IBR5V ArticleBylines_twoCol__rmKE3"><address id="byline">By <a class="ArticleBylines_link__kNP4C" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/author/chris-heath/" data-action="click author - byline" data-label="https://www.theatlantic.com/author/chris-heath/" data-event-element="author" data-flatplan-author-link="true">Chris Heath</a><div>Photographs by Lila Barth</div></address></div></div></div><div class="ArticleLeadArt_root__nRSLU ArticleLeadArt_twoCol__XedW5"><figure class="ArticleLeadFigure_root__Bj81R"><div class="ArticleLeadFigure_media__R1npW" data-flatplan-lead_figure_media="true"><picture><img alt="A close up photograph of actor Daniel Radcliffe." class="Image_root__XxsOp ArticleLeadArt_image__HZS4B" sizes="(min-width: 1440px) 656px, (min-width:1024px) calc(50vw - 64px), (min-width: 768px) calc(50vw - 48px), (min-width: 375px) calc(100vw - 103px), (min-width: 320px) calc(100vw - 64px), calc(100vw - 48px)" srcSet="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/wSzaHurW9YBXy00B7XCZ324-3KU=/0x0:2399x2999/296x370/media/img/2024/04/29/BoB_Heath_RadcliffeOpenerArticle/original.png 296w, https://c